\label{sec:gas}



To compare the energies and angular sizes above with the expectations from models of feedback, we can construct a simple model of gas heating with and without AGN feedback.   
To do this we first compute $R_{\rm vir},$ the virial radius of a (spherical) dark matter halo defined as the physical radius within which the density is 200 times the mean cosmic value.  As a function of redshift $z$ and mass $M,$ this is

text:
\begin{equation} 
T_{\rm vir} = \frac{G M}{R_{\rm vir}}   \frac{\mu m_p}{2 k}  = 2.4 \times 10^6 {\rm K} \, M^{2/3}_{13}  (1+z),
\label{model:Tvir}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
E_{\rm therm,gravity} &= \frac{3 k T_{\rm vir}}{2} \frac{\Omega_b}{\Omega_0} \frac{M}{\mu m_p} \\  &=

1.5 \times 10^{60} \, {\rm ergs} \, M_{13}^{5/3} (1+z).
\label{eq:Etherm}
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
M_{\rm stellar} &= 6.6_{-3.2}^{+5.5}  \times 10^{10} \, M_\odot \,\left(\frac{v_{\rm c}}{300 \, {\rm km~s^{-1}}}\right)^{5}\\
 &= 2.8_{-1.4}^{+2.4}  \times 10^{10} M_\odot   \,  M_{13}^{5/3} (1+z)^{5/2},
 \label{eq:Mstellar}
\end{split}
\end{equation}

